                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d172">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5419: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1" type="from">Cunningham</persName>) to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-18T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 18, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 18—6:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>339. Referring to my telegram No. 337, July 15, 4 p.m.,<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d172fn3">Not printed.</note> area D turned over to Chinese 11 a.m.
                    of 17th witnessed by <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BLRA1">Boone</persName>.
                    Only outside points still occupied by Japanese are Toyoda Mill, Jessfield Road
                    and Kung Dah Mill, Pingliang Road. Each mill is on an extra-Settlement road. The
                    Chinese intend to press for evacuation of the two mills. These two mills were
                    occupied prior to January 28 by Japanese military and present garrisons do not
                    exceed 200 and 150.</p>
                <p>Repeated to the Legation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
